sage.scene

Class Material

  • java.lang.Object
    • sage.scene.Material
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    OBJMaterial

    public abstract class Material
extends java.lang.Object
    This class defines an abstraction for Material objects -- that is, objects defining a material which can be applied to scene elements. Each material contains the following attributes:
    • name: a String giving the name associated with this material.
    • ambient coefficients: a set of three values, each in the range [0..1], indicating the amount of ambient light reflection for each of R,G, and B.
    • diffuse coefficients: a set of three values, each in the range [0..1], indicating the amount of diffuse light reflection for each of R,G, and B.
    • specular coefficients: a set of three values, each in the range [0..1], indicating the amount of specular light reflection for each of R,G, and B.
    • emissive coefficients: a set of three values, each in the range [0..1], indicating the amount of emitted light for each of R,G, and B.
    • shininess: a positive value giving the specular reflection coefficient; that is, the degree to which the material focuses specular reflections along the true reflection vector. Higher values produce narrower focus, resulting in materials having a higher "shininess" or "glossiness".
    • transparency: a value in the range [0..1] indicating the transparency of the material. Note that this value is represented in terms of opacity, the reciprocal of "transparency". That is, when the value of this attribute is 1 the material is totally opaque (has zero transparency).
    • index of refraction: the refraction index indicating how much light bends when it passes through this material.
    • texture file name: a String giving the name of the file to be used for texture mapping with this material. Note that the current Material implementation only supports a single texture map per material (that is, multi-texturing using multiple hardware texture units is not supported).
    Author:
    John Clevenger

        public abstract int loadMaterial(java.io.BufferedReader br)

      • loadMaterial

        public abstract boolean loadMaterial()
        Loads this material with data from an internally-determined source (for example, prompts for the name of a material definition file and loads from that file). It is up to subclasses to define the mechanism for determining the material definition source.
        Returns:
        True if the material was successfully loaded; false otherwise.
